2.  **Hereditary**: If $I$ is matchable, then for any $J \subseteq I$, $J$ is also matchable. If $I$ is matchable, there exists a matching $M$ such that $I \subseteq V(G, M)$. Since $J \subseteq I$, we have $J \subseteq V(G, M)$. So, we can use the same matching $M$ to show that $J$ is matchable.

