This lemma shows that any prefix of an alternating path is also an alternating path. This is true because the property of being an alternating path is preserved under taking prefixes.

```tactics
lemma IsAltPath.mem_matching_iff {P : WList α β} (h : G.IsAltPath hM P) :
    P.edge.IsChain (fun e f ↦ e ∈ M ↔ f ∉ M) := by
  match P with
  | .nil u => simp
  | .cons u e (.nil v) => simp
  | .cons u e (.cons v f w) =>
    simp only [WList.cons_edge, List.isChain_cons_cons]
    obtain ⟨hor, -⟩ := by simpa using h.mem_matching
    obtain ⟨⟨hef, -⟩, -, -⟩ := by simpa using h.isTrail.edge_nodup
    obtain ⟨⟨-, hfvwf, -⟩, heuv, -, -⟩ := by simpa using h.toIsPath
    use ⟨fun heM hfM ↦ ?_, hor.resolve_right⟩, by simpa using h.of_cons.mem_matching_iff
    exact hM.disjoint heM hfM hef |>.notMem_of_mem_left heuv.inc_right hfvwf.inc_left
```

This lemma characterizes the structure of the edges in an alternating path. It shows that the edges in the path alternate between being in $M$ and not being in $M$. This is the defining property of an alternating path.

